Introduction

In lecture, we have been discussing the idea of correlation. This is the idea that two things that we measure can be somehow related to one another. For example, your personal happiness, which we could try to measure say with a questionnaire, might be related to other things in your life that we could also measure, such as number of close friends, yearly salary, how much chocolate you have in your bedroom, or how many times you have said the word Nintendo in your life. Some of the relationships that we can measure are meaningful, and might reflect a causal relationship where one thing causes a change in another thing. Some of the relationships are spurious, and do not reflect a causal relationship.

In this lab you will learn how to compute correlations between two variables in ‘R’, and then ask some questions about the correlations that you observe.

Learning Goals

  1. Compute Pearson’s r between two variables with R
  2. Simple linear regression with R
  3. Discuss the possible meaning of correlations that you observe

Data

We use data from the World Happiness Report. The World Happiness Report is a landmark survey of the state of global happiness that ranks 166 countries by how happy their citizens perceive themselves to be.
A csv of the data for the year 2021 is included in the lab materials. The data includes annual survey results from the year 2008 to 2020 for each of the 166 countries. Beware that there is missing values (‘NA’) for some of the columns.

Let’s load the data:

# Make sure the data are in the right folder
# 
whr_data <- read.csv('./WHR2021.csv')


# Now browse the data and see what columns the data have. The names of the column should explain themselves
names(whr_data)

# Show the first few rows of the data frame.
head(whr_data)

You should be able to see that there is data for many different countries, across a few different years. There are lots of different kinds of measures, and each are given a name that should explain themselves. You can find out more info here: https://worldhappiness.report/faq/

Getting Familiar with the Data

Life Satisfaction over time

One of the most interesting columns is the Life.Ladder'' variable. This is a descriptor of life satisfaction and happiness. From the WHR website:This is called the Cantril ladder: it asks respondents to think of a ladder, with the best possible life for them being a 10, and the worst possible life being a 0. They are then asked to rate their own current lives on that 0 to 10 scale.’’ Then WHR calculates the mean rating for each country and that’s the value you see in ``Life.Ladder’’

To start, let’s explore the changes of the Life.Ladder over the years for the United States.

# By using dplyr, we can easily select the rows and columns in the dataframe that we want
# Then save it to a new dataframe called "whr_data_us"
whr_data_us <- whr_data %>%
  select(country, year, Life.Ladder) %>% #select the interested columns
  filter(country == 'United States')  # only choose United States

# Plot
ggplot(whr_data_us) + aes(x=year, y=Life.Ladder) + geom_line() +
  ggtitle("US Mean Life.Ladder, 2008 - 2020")

Life Satisfaction over time: comparing countries

It looks like life satisfaction has dropped a bit over the last decade in the United States, but seen a small rebound in the last few years. Let’s look at another country to compare between the two. In this case, we’ll use Germany

# By using dplyr, we can easily select the rows and columns in the dataframe that we want
# Then we save it to a new dataframe called "whr_data_us_germany"
whr_data_us_germany <- whr_data %>%
  select(country, year, Life.Ladder) %>% #select the interested columns
  filter(country == 'United States' | country == 'Germany')  # choose US AND Germany

# Plot, using "country" as the color aesthetic
ggplot(whr_data_us_germany) + aes(x=year, y=Life.Ladder, color=country) + geom_line() +
  ggtitle("Mean Life.Ladder, 2008 - 2020")

Calculating Correlation

Does a countries measure for “Freedom.to.make.life.choices” correlate with that countries measure for “Life.Ladder”?

Let’s find out. We calculate the correlation, and then we make the scatter plot.

cor(whr_data$Freedom.to.make.life.choices, whr_data$Life.Ladder)
## [1] NA
ggplot(whr_data) + aes(x=Freedom.to.make.life.choices, y=Life.Ladder) + geom_point()

What happened here? We can see some dots, but the correlation was NA (meaning missing values or undefined). This occurred because there are some missing data points in the data. We can remove all the rows with missing data first, then do the correlation. We will do this a couple steps, first creating our own data.frame with only the numbers we want to analyse. Similar with the previous case, we can select the columns we want to keep using select(). Then we use filter() to remove the rows with NAs (! means NOT, so !is.na() means NOT NA)

# Remove NA rows and save it as a new dataframe
smaller_df <- whr_data %>%
               select(country,
                      Freedom.to.make.life.choices,
                      Life.Ladder) %>%
               filter(!is.na(Freedom.to.make.life.choices), # ! means NOT, so !is.na() means NOT NA
                      !is.na(Life.Ladder))

# Calculate correlation!
cor(smaller_df$Freedom.to.make.life.choices,
    smaller_df$Life.Ladder)
## [1] 0.5280633

Now we see the correlation is .528. That’s a pretty strong positive correlation!

Adding line of best fit

Although the scatter plot shows the dots are everywhere, it generally shows that as Freedom to make life choices increases in a country, that country’s life satisfaction (Life.Ladder) also increase. This is a positive correlation. Let’s do this again and add the best fit line, so the trend is more clear. The function to fit the line or simple regression is lm(), and the way to use it is lm(y~x) where y~x is the formula to be fitted, y is the response or dependent variable, x is the explanatory/independent variable, and ~ sign is a separator. Type ?lm to see more about how to use this function.

# first make the scatter plot
ggplot(smaller_df) + aes(x=Freedom.to.make.life.choices, y=Life.Ladder) + geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method='lm', formula=y~x) # Then add the line of best fit! It's as easy as that!

Linear Modeling

In the last code block, we had ggplot fit a linear model and add that line to our plot (with some error margins)

Here, we’ll fit the same linear model and investigate it more

To fit a linear model in R, you use the lm() command. Inside the command, you give it a formula with the variables you want to model: lm(y~x) Notice how the y variable comes FIRST and the x comes SECOND. How you can read this is target variable ~ predictor variable

Let’s fit a linear model predicting Life.Ladder (target variable) using Freedom.to.make.life.choices (predictor variable)

linear_model <- lm(whr_data$Life.Ladder~whr_data$Freedom.to.make.life.choices)

What lm(y~x) does is to fit the simple linear regression model y = a + bx. In other words, lm() can estimate the coefficients a (intercept) and b (slope). We can assess the intercept and slope like the following:

# show the summary of the fitted linear model
summary(linear_model)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = whr_data$Life.Ladder ~ whr_data$Freedom.to.make.life.choices)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -3.04806 -0.64406  0.04139  0.76966  2.64759 
## 
## Coefficients:
##                                       Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)                             2.3758     0.1157   20.54   <2e-16 ***
## whr_data$Freedom.to.make.life.choices   4.1633     0.1530   27.21   <2e-16 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 0.9516 on 1915 degrees of freedom
##   (32 observations deleted due to missingness)
## Multiple R-squared:  0.2789, Adjusted R-squared:  0.2785 
## F-statistic: 740.5 on 1 and 1915 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16
# We can access the fitted intercepts and slope values
linear_model$coefficients # this is a vector with two entries, the first one is intercept and other is slope
##                           (Intercept) whr_data$Freedom.to.make.life.choices 
##                              2.375825                              4.163252
linear_model$coefficients[1] # is the intercept
## (Intercept) 
##    2.375825
linear_model$coefficients[2] # is the slope
## whr_data$Freedom.to.make.life.choices 
##                              4.163252
